  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">HIRDA is an acronym of Himilo Relief and development Association, a non-profit and non-political organization founded in 1998 in Den Haag by Somali refugees in the Netherlands. The purpose of the organization was to take part in the reconstruction and humanitarian effort in Somalia, promote basic education, gender mainstreaming, encourage the integration and engagement in development among the Somali community in the Netherlands.

HIRDA started its education support programme in 1999 after the collapseof education system in Bardera city following the collapse of the Said Barre government in 1991. Since then HIRDA has been involved in other developmentactivities in Gedo, Galgudud and other regions in southern and northern Somalia. It is now engaged ineducation, health, relief, support orphans,  peace and human rights, women empowerment, water improvement and other projects in south and central Somalia and Somaliland. (see more strategic plan)

The proposed project uses a holistic approach to tacklethe key factors driving insecurity for poor and vulnerable pastoralist and agro-pastoralist communities in 6 districts of Somali region, Ethiopia, and 10 locations in the Galbeed and Togdheer areas of the Somaliland region of Somalia. Oxfam is working inthese fragile areas, recognizing the imperative of supporting reconstruction and decrease destabilizing factors due to the volatile political dynamics inherent in the region and the frequent crisis of drought.

This project is laying the foundations for building resilient communities and improving the humansecurityof pastoralists along the Ethiopia-Somaliland border by using a holistic approach to tackle the integrated causes of conflict.   This project is a multi affiliate/ multipartner project, HIRDA will be responsible and implement activities that contribute to Increased capacity of Civil society including groups of women, youth and men  to participate in (community and district levels) and influence (national level) forums and processesThe activitiesproposed in this project will Include:
# Identify key social and policy issuesof targeted community groups
# Conduct power analysis to identify community, district and national level policy targets and allies/partners
# Assess leadership/capacitylevels of targeted community groups, disaggregated by gender
# Leadership training and mentoring for women and youth groups based on assessment
# Learning visits to other inspirational women#s groups/leaders
# Youth awareness raising of NRM and negative impacts of charcoal production
# Facilitate community groups (including women and youth) to engage with traditional and formal institutions, including on natural resource management (NRM) policy development
# Conduct discussion on genderroles, violence against women with different groups (women#s groups, men, CBDRM committee members, NRM committees)</narrative>
  </description>
